"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Timothy chapter 6 (all 21 verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1timothy-6-6.py

Historical-cultural context: Ephesian setting; Roman slavery institution; Stoic
autarkeia; sophist fee-charging controversy; Greco-Roman agōn culture; Hellenistic
epiphaneia; Roman euergetism/benefaction; parathēkē (legal deposit) in Roman law;
syncretistic mystery-cult milieu at Ephesus.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "6": {
    "1": '<p>Roman slavery was pervasive in the empire — estimates suggest 30-40% of the Italian population and 10-15% in the provinces were enslaved. Slaves ranged from agricultural laborers to educated household managers, physicians, and tutors. A slave\'s legal status was that of property (<em>res mancipi</em>), yet in urban households especially, skilled slaves often exercised significant authority and could expect eventual manumission. The Ephesian church likely included slaves from wealthy pagan households — a socially delicate situation where a slave\'s new religious identity might be seen as destabilizing to the household order.</p><p>The missional rationale — respecting masters so that "God\'s name and the teaching may not be slandered" — reflects acute early Christian awareness of the social gaze. Christians were already viewed with suspicion as an antisocial movement; slaves who used their new status as pretext for insubordination would confirm the worst accusations.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The scenario of v. 2 — a slave with a believing master — presented a distinct social complexity. Christian brotherhood in principle leveled social distinctions (Gal 3:28; Phlm 16), but if slaves took egalitarian theology as license for contempt toward masters, it would destabilize the household (<em>oikos</em>) that functioned as the church\'s primary gathering space. The wealthy householder who hosted the congregation (cf. Rom 16:23; 1 Cor 16:19) was also the employer or owner of some of its members. The letter navigates a real social tension without abolishing the institution — the longer arc toward liberation runs through transformed relationships rather than immediate structural revolt.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The charge of "teaching otherwise" (<em>heterodidaskalein</em>) operates in a context where Ephesus was a city of competing philosophical and religious teachers. Wandering teachers — Stoic, Cynic, Pythagorean, Jewish, and proto-Christian — circulated through Asia Minor\'s cities, establishing followings and teaching publicly in the agora, baths, and private homes. The question of whose teaching was "sound" or "healthy" was a live social debate; philosophical schools regularly charged rivals with corrupting youth or undermining civic virtue. Paul\'s language of "healthy words" versus diseased teaching maps onto this competitive teacher landscape.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Controversies and "word-battles" (<em>logomachias</em>) were not merely abstract theological disputes — they were a recognized social phenomenon in Greco-Roman intellectual culture. Rhetorical contests (<em>agōnes</em>) between sophists attracted audiences; verbal sparring was entertainment and status-display. The Stoic tradition distinguished between genuine philosophical dialogue and mere eristic debate (verbal combat for victory rather than truth). Paul\'s characterization of the false teachers as "diseased about controversies" draws on the same tradition that distinguished the virtuous philosopher from the showman-sophist. The vice list that follows — envy, strife, slander, evil suspicions, constant friction — maps the social damage of competitive factionalism.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The accusation that the false teachers treat godliness as a "means of profit" (<em>porizmos</em>) engages directly with a live controversy about charging fees for philosophical or religious instruction. Sophists were notorious for charging high fees; the Socratic tradition (as reported in Plato\'s dialogues) explicitly rejected fee-charging as corruptive of the philosophical relationship. Traveling Jewish teachers who charged for Torah instruction were also criticized. Paul\'s own refusal to take money from some communities (1 Cor 9) while accepting it from others (Phil 4:15) shows him navigating the same social minefield. The accusation that the Ephesian teachers monetize religion is the most damaging charge that could be leveled against a philosophical or religious teacher in this environment.</p>',
    "6": '<p><em>Autarkeia</em> (contentment/self-sufficiency) was one of the central virtues of Hellenistic philosophical ethics. The Stoics held that the wise person is <em>autarkēs</em> — self-sufficient, independent of fortune, external goods, or other people. The Cynics practiced this more radically: Diogenes in his barrel, owning nothing. The philosophical ideal crossed into popular culture as a recognized mark of the truly virtuous person. Paul adopts the vocabulary (<em>autarkeia</em>) but displaces its ground: not inner virtue or philosophical training but godliness — relationship with God — is the true source of self-sufficiency. The Stoic goal is borrowed but re-rooted in covenant rather than character cultivation.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The maxim "we brought nothing into the world and can take nothing out" was a recognized philosophical and wisdom commonplace in the ancient world. It appears in various forms in Seneca (<em>Ep.</em> 77.11), Cicero (<em>Tusc.</em> 1.48), and closely parallels Job 1:21 and Eccl 5:15. This was not a uniquely Pauline or specifically Christian observation — it was received wisdom from multiple traditions. The function of citing a shared commonplace is rhetorical: the audience already agrees with the premise, so the practical conclusion (contentment with basic necessities) appears as obvious wisdom rather than religious demand.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The identification of "food and covering" (<em>diatrophas kai skepas</em>) as sufficient for contentment echoes Stoic and Cynic diatribe literature on the minimal requirements of the good life. The Cynics reduced human need to the absolute minimum; the Stoics spoke of "preferred indifferents" — things like health, wealth, and comfort that are desirable but not necessary for virtue. The rabbinic tradition similarly emphasized that a person needs only bread and water to live, with shelter as the third basic need. The convergence of Jewish wisdom, Stoic ethics, and the Cynic simplicity tradition gave Paul\'s practical conclusion broad cultural traction in the Ephesian environment.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The image of the wealth-seeker plunging into "temptation and a trap" uses the language of hunting (<em>pagida</em> = snare) common in wisdom and ethical literature for describing how vices ensnare the unwary. The metaphor of being submerged or drowned (<em>bythizousin</em>, from <em>bythos</em>, depth) — "plunging into ruin" — is nautical, evoking shipwreck as the consequence of wealth-chasing. The Greco-Roman moralist tradition (Seneca, Dio Chrysostom, Epictetus) regularly warned about wealth as the source of slavery to desire rather than the gateway to freedom it appeared to offer — a warning that would resonate in the commercial port city of Ephesus.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Love of money is a root of all kinds of evil" (<em>hē philarguria rhiza pantōn tōn kakōn</em>) echoes formulations found across the Hellenistic philosophical tradition. Democritus, Diodorus Siculus, and Bion of Borysthenes all have versions of "love of money is the mother-city of all evils." The formulation was a proverb-like commonplace rather than original to Paul. What Paul adds is the specifically Christian dimension: some who have pursued <em>philarguria</em> have "wandered from the faith" — the philosophical commonplace about moral corruption from wealth-love is given an ecclesial charge. The Ephesian false teachers exemplify both the philosophical and theological failure simultaneously.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Man of God" (<em>anthrōpe theou</em>) is an OT prophetic title applied specifically to Moses (Deut 33:1), Samuel (1 Sam 9:6), Elijah (1 Kgs 17:18), and Elisha (2 Kgs 4:9). Its application to Timothy situates him within the prophetic covenant-guardian tradition rather than merely in the role of a Greco-Roman philosophical teacher or religious functionary. In a city dominated by the Artemis cult, mystery religions, and itinerant wonder-workers, the claim that Timothy stands in the succession of Israel\'s prophets is a counter-cultural identity marker. The six-virtue list that follows (<em>righteousness, godliness, faith, love, endurance, gentleness</em>) resembles both Hellenistic virtue catalogues and OT descriptions of covenant character.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The athletic metaphor of "fighting the good fight" (<em>agōnizou ton kalon agōna</em>) drew on one of the most vivid cultural realities of the Greco-Roman world: the great athletic games. The Olympian, Pythian, Isthmian, and Nemean games were the defining events of Panhellenic culture; civic identity was deeply bound up with athletic competition and the honor it generated. The philosophical tradition from Plato onward used the <em>agōn</em> (contest) as an image for the life of virtue: the philosopher as athlete of the soul. Epictetus, writing from roughly the same period, uses extensive athletic imagery for moral formation. The "confession before many witnesses" likely evokes a public liturgical setting — baptismal confession, ordination vow, or similar — performed before the assembled congregation.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The reference to Pontius Pilate provides one of the NT\'s rare explicit historical anchors. Pilate served as prefect of Judaea from 26-36 CE; his name and role in Jesus\'s execution were known through both Christian tradition and wider Roman awareness (Tacitus, <em>Ann.</em> 15.44 names him). The Roman provincial judicial setting — interrogation of a defendant before the prefect in a public tribunal — is the context for "making the good confession." Roman trials were public spectacles; a defendant\'s courage or capitulation under examination was itself a civic performance. The Pastoral Epistles use Christ\'s testimony before Pilate as the paradigm for Timothy\'s own public witness — the faithful <em>martys</em> (witness) faces public pressure with the same unflinching confession.</p>',
    "14": '<p><em>Epiphaneia</em> (appearing) was a well-established technical term in Hellenistic religious and political culture. In ruler cult, the <em>epiphaneia</em> was the formal public appearance of a king — celebrated with feasts, games, and civic honor — simultaneously understood as a manifestation of divine presence. The term was also used for the manifestation of a god in dream, oracle, or cultic event. The Seleucid king Antiochus IV notoriously took the title <em>Epiphanes</em> ("God manifest"). Paul\'s use of <em>epiphaneia</em> for the Parousia deliberately co-opts the royal and divine-manifestation vocabulary, claiming for Jesus\'s return the kind of world-altering significance that Hellenistic culture attributed to the arrival of a god-king.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"King of kings and Lord of lords" was royal titulature with deep political resonance. The title appears in Persian royal inscriptions (Artaxerxes II as "king of kings"), in the OT for pagan kings (Ezek 26:7 calls Nebuchadnezzar "king of kings"), and in Daniel for God\'s supreme sovereignty (Dan 2:47). By Paul\'s time, the imperial Roman court appropriated similar universal sovereignty language for the emperor. The doxological application of the title to "the blessed and only Sovereign" is therefore a counter-imperial claim: the true King of kings is not the emperor in Rome but the God of Israel and his Christ — whose <em>epiphaneia</em> will expose the pretension of all rival sovereigns.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Unapproachable light" (<em>phōs aprositon</em>) combines the OT theophanies (divine glory as fire and light: Exod 24:17, Ps 104:2) with Hellenistic-Jewish philosophical speculation about God as pure light. Philo of Alexandria and later Neoplatonism developed extensive traditions about the divine as ineffable light beyond all created light. The statement "whom no one has seen or can see" aligns with Exod 33:20 and the broader Jewish tradition of divine inaccessibility. The doxological shape of vv. 15-16 suggests liturgical usage — a hymn fragment or creedal formula known to the Ephesian community, perhaps used in their worship assemblies before Paul incorporated it here.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The wealthy (<em>plousioi</em>) in the Greco-Roman city bore specific social obligations through the system of <em>euergetism</em> (benefaction): the rich were expected to fund civic buildings, games, grain distributions, and temple dedications in exchange for public honor (inscriptions, front-row seats, statues). Wealth was the basis of social standing and civic power. The instruction not to "be arrogant" (<em>hypsēlophronein</em>) and not to set hope "on the uncertainty of wealth" directly challenges the dominant social logic of the Greco-Roman city, where wealth was precisely the ground of pride and public confidence. Stoic and Cynic writers regularly noted wealth\'s volatility — fire, shipwreck, and political reversal could eliminate it overnight — so this was a recognized danger even in secular ethics.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The instruction to "do good" (<em>agathoergein</em>), "be generous" (<em>eumetadotous</em>), and "willing to share" (<em>koinōnikous</em>) redirects the wealthy from the dominant honor-seeking model of Greco-Roman benefaction toward a different social economy. Greco-Roman <em>euergetism</em> gave publicly and selectively — to the city as a whole, to clients who would advertise the patron\'s generosity, to institutions that would inscribe the donor\'s name in stone. The Christian counter-model was horizontal generosity within the community, without expectation of reciprocal social honor. The vocabulary of <em>koinōnia</em> (sharing-partnership) frames wealth-sharing as communion rather than patronage.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The image of "storing up treasure" (<em>apothēsaurizein</em>) as a foundation for the coming age draws on Jewish apocalyptic traditions where almsgiving and generosity were explicitly conceived as treasures stored in heaven (Tobit 4:9; 2 Bar. 14:12; 1 En. 38:2). Jesus\'s teaching on "treasure in heaven" (Matt 6:19-21; Luke 12:33) likely activated this same tradition for the early church. The economic metaphor — invest in eschatological currency rather than the depreciating currency of this age — provides a rationale for counter-cultural generosity that speaks directly to the wealthy person\'s long-term interest, translating the abstract call to virtue into the familiar framework of prudent investment.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The <em>parathēkē</em> (deposit, trust) was a recognized legal institution in Roman law. Under the <em>actio depositi</em>, a person could entrust valuable property to a trusted custodian (<em>depositarius</em>) with the legal obligation to return it intact on demand. The custodian bore fiduciary responsibility; to dissipate or misuse the deposit was both a legal wrong and a breach of personal honor. Applying this legal-commercial metaphor to apostolic teaching — Timothy is the custodian of doctrine entrusted to him by Paul — frames theological fidelity in terms of the most serious personal obligation the Greco-Roman world recognized: the fiduciary duty of an entrusted steward.</p><p>"Falsely named knowledge" (<em>gnōsis pseudōnymos</em>) targets the errorists\' claim to superior knowledge. Ephesus was a center of mystery religions (the Artemis cult), magical practice (the famous "Ephesian letters" — amulet formulas), and philosophical-religious syncretism. Esoteric knowledge claims were a feature of multiple Ephesian-area groups. Whether the false teaching was proto-Gnostic in the technical sense or a local form of Jewish esoteric speculation, the label <em>pseudōnymos</em> (falsely named) refutes the knowledge-claim in the title itself.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The closing "Grace be with you all" (<em>hē charis meth\' hymōn</em>) uses a plural "you" despite the letter being formally addressed to Timothy. This is a standard feature of the Pastoral Epistles and confirms that the letter, while having Timothy as its named recipient, was intended for public reading in the Ephesian congregation. Reading letters aloud in the assembled community was the normal mode of Pauline letter reception (cf. Col 4:16; 1 Thess 5:27). The congregation at Ephesus is the real audience; Timothy is simultaneously the addressee and the carrier of the letter\'s authority to the community he shepherds.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '1timothy')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1timothy', existing)

    il = json.loads((ROOT / 'data' / 'interlinear' / '1timothy.json').read_text())
    all_ok = True
    for ch in ['6']:
        il_vv = set(il.get(ch, {}).keys())
        out_vv = set(existing.get(ch, {}).keys())
        missing = il_vv - out_vv
        if missing:
            print(f'  ch{ch} still missing: {sorted(missing, key=int)}')
            all_ok = False
        else:
            print(f'  ch{ch}: complete ({len(out_vv)} verses)')
    if all_ok:
        print('All 1 Tim ch6 context entries present ✓')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
